# Documentation and code comments

## Documentation

- Keep **all** project documentation accurate when behaviour, versions, remotes, tooling, or standards change.
- Update the README, `docs/**`, `AGENTS.md`, changelogs, and any feature-specific markdown in the same change set when those topics are affected — do not leave stale version numbers, test counts, Node/npm ranges, or archived/outdated guidance.
- Prefer linking to canonical docs (`AGENTS.md`, `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`, `docs/readme/*`) rather than duplicating conflicting instructions.
- Document **why** a decision was made when it is non-obvious (for example Nest DI coverage transform, pinned TypeScript 6 vs 7, GOV.UK macro usage).
- After dependency or GOV.UK Frontend upgrades, sync version tables and status sections in README and docs.

## TypeScript documentation comments (TSDoc-compatible JSDoc)

Use `/** ... */` blocks that follow [TSDoc](https://tsdoc.org/) conventions and [TypeScript’s documentation tags](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/jsdoc-supported-types.html) (`@deprecated`, `@see`, `{@link}`).

### Required style

- **Summary first** (one short paragraph). Put longer constraints under `@remarks`.
- **Do not restate types** in comments — the TypeScript signature is the source of truth.
  - Good: `@param logger - Logger for security monitoring`
  - Bad: `@param {LoggerService} logger - ...` or `@returns {Promise<void>}`
- Use a hyphen after names: `@param name - Description`, `@throws Error - When …`.
- Omit `@returns` when it only repeats the return type with no useful description.
- Prefer `{@link Symbol}` / `@see` for cross-references; mark retired APIs with `@deprecated`.
- Call out security-sensitive behaviour (CSRF, headers, sanitisation), performance traps, and GOV.UK Frontend macro/template requirements in the summary or `@remarks`.

### Do not use

- `@module`, `@requires`, `@class`, `@interface`, `@function`, `@async` — redundant with imports and TypeScript syntax.
- JSDoc `{Type}` braces on `@param`, `@returns`, `@throws`, `@template`, or `@property` in `.ts` files.

### Coverage

- Every public module, class, and non-trivial function should have a clear documentation block (purpose, important inputs/outputs behaviour, side effects, constraints).
- Explain **why** and **constraints**, not a line-by-line restatement of obvious code.
- Keep Nunjucks templates annotated where macros are composed or where client scripts depend on macro-rendered markup.
- When changing code, update nearby comments and any related documentation in the same change — never leave comments that contradict the code.

### Enforcement

- ESLint: `jsdoc/no-types` (error), hyphen-before-param-description, banned redundant tags, and `tsdoc/syntax` (see `eslint.config.js`).
- Extended TSDoc tags for this app live in `tsdoc.json` (`@template`, `@default`, `@todo`).
- Do not add TypeDoc / API Extractor unless we publish a library API surface.
- When retiring an API, mark it with `@deprecated` so editors strike it through.

## Agent checklist

When finishing a change:

1. Docs touched or confirmed still accurate for that change
2. Public/complex APIs have up-to-date TSDoc-compatible comments (no typed `{Type}` braces)
3. `AGENTS.md` / `.cursor/rules` updated if a standing convention changed
